atch2_HFX_FCE={{small|Oct 4}}\n|match2_HFX_FOR={{small|Sep 2}}\n|match2_HFX_OTT={{small|Jun 5}}\n|match2_HFX_PAC={{small|Aug 3}}\n|match2_HFX_VAL={{small|Sep 19}}\n|match2_HFX_YOR={{small|Sep 12}}\n\n|match1_PAC_CAV={{small|May 30}}\n|match1_PAC_FCE={{small|Apr 11}}\n|match1_PAC_FOR={{small|May 8}}\n|match1_PAC_HFX={{small|Apr 17}}\n|match1_PAC_OTT={{small|Jul 1}}\n|match1_PAC_VAL={{small|Apr 26}}\n|match1_PAC_YOR={{small|Jul 29}}\n|match2_PAC_CAV={{small|Sep 13}}\n|match2_PAC_FCE={{small|Jul 12}}\n|match2_PAC_FOR={{small|Sep 19}}\n|match2_PAC_HFX={{small|Aug 14}}\n|match2_PAC_OTT={{small|Aug 25}}\n|match2_PAC_VAL={{small|Jun 6}}\n|match2_PAC_YOR={{small|Oct 4}}\n\n|match1_VAL_CAV={{small|Aug 9}}\n|match1_VAL_FCE={{small|May 9}}\n|match1_VAL_FOR={{small|Jul 1}}\n|match1_VAL_HFX={{small|May 29}}\n|match1_VAL_OTT={{small|May 2}}\n|match1_VAL_PAC={{small|Jun 13}}\n|match1_VAL_YOR={{small|Aug 22}}\n|match2_VAL_CAV={{small|Sep 6}}\n|match2_VAL_FCE={{small|Aug 2}}\n|match2_VAL_FOR={{small|Jul 22}}\n|match2_VAL_HFX={{small|Jul 25}}\n|match2_VAL_OTT={{small|Jul 12}}\n|match2_VAL_PAC={{small|Aug 29}}\n|match2_VAL_YOR={{small|Sep 26}}\n\n|match1_YOR_CAV={{small|Aug 26}}\n|match1_YOR_FCE={{small|May 1}}\n|match1_YOR_FOR={{small|Jun 12}}\n|match1_YOR_HFX={{small|Apr 13}}\n|match1_YOR_OTT={{small|May 8}}\n|match1_YOR_PAC={{small|Jun 28}}\n|match1_YOR_VAL={{small|Apr 17}}\n|match2_YOR_CAV={{small|Jul 10}}\n|match2_YOR_FCE={{small|May 22}}\n|match2_YOR_FOR={{small|Aug 2}}\n|match2_YOR_HFX={{small|Aug 7}}\n|match2_YOR_OTT={{small|Jul 24}}\n|match2_YOR_PAC={{small|Sep 4}}\n|match2_YOR_VAL={{small|Jun 19}}\n}}\n\n==Playoff and finals==\n{{main|2020 Canadian Premier League Finals}}\nWith the change to a single table regular season comes a change to the post-season, with the introduction of a two round play-off. The first place team in the regular season will qualify directly to the 2020 CPL Finals, while the second and third place teams will compete in a playoff to determine the second spot in the Finals.<ref>{{cite news |title=BEDAKIAN: Single-table, playoff soccer has come to the CPL \u2013 and it's beautiful |url=https://canpl.ca/article/bedakian-single-table-playoff-soccer-has-come-to-the-cpl-and-its-beautiful |accessdate=21 February 2020 |publisher=Canadian Premier League}}</ref>\n\n===Bracket===\n{{3TeamBracket\n|RD1 =[[2020 Canadian Premier League Finals#Playoff|Playoff]]\n|RD2 = [[2020 Canadian Premier League Finals|Finals]]\n|RD1-seed1 = 2\n|RD1-team1 = \n|RD1-score1 = \n|RD1-seed2 = 3\n|RD1-team2 = \n|RD1-score2 = \n|RD2-seed1 = 1\n|RD2-team1 = \n|RD2-score1 = \n|RD2-seed2 = &nbsp;\n|RD2-team2 = \n|RD2-score2 = \n}}\n\n== Player transfers ==\n{{Main|List of 2020 Canadian Premier League transfers|l1=Canadian Premier League transfers 2020}}\n\n=== U Sports Draft ===\n{{further|2019 CPL\u2013U Sports Draft}}\n\nThe [[2019 CPL\u2013U Sports Draft]] was held on November 11 in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]]. Draftees will be invited to team preseason camps, with an opportunity to earn a developmental contract and retain their [[U Sports men's soccer]] eligibility. [[HFX Wanderers FC|HFX Wanderers]] selected Cory Bent with the first overall pick. Two players were selected by each returning CPL team, with a total of 14 players being drafted including 10 Canadians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/live-2019-cpl-u-sports-draft-tracker-follow-all-14-picks|title=TRACKER: All 14 picks from the 2019 CPL-U SPORTS Draft|date=November 11, 2019|website=Canadian Premier League|language=en-CA|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> Ottawa had not yet joined the league and did not participate in the draft.\n\n=== Foreign players ===\nCanadian Premier League teams may sign a maximum of seven international players, out of which only five can be in the starting line-up for each match. The following players are considered foreign players for the 2020 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/cpl-off-season-roster-tracker-whos-in-and-whos-out-for-2020|title=CPL off-season roster tracker: Who's in and who's out for 2020?|date=November 4, 2019|website=Canadian Premier League|language=en-CA|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe list does not include Canadian citizens who represent other countries at the international level.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Club\n!Player 1\n!Player 2\n!Player 3\n!Player 4\n!Player 5\n!Player 6\n!Player 7\n|-\n|[[Atl\u00e9tico Ottawa]]\n|{{Flagicon|England}} [[Vashon Neufville]]\n|{{Flagicon|Jamaica}} [[Tevin Shaw]]\n|{{Flagicon|Mexico}} [[Francisco Acu\u00f1a]]\n|{{Flagicon|Ghana}} [[Bernardinho (footballer)|Bernardinho]]\n|{{Flagicon|Spain}} [[Ignacio Zabal|Nacho Zabal]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Cavalry FC|Cavalry]]\n|{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Oliver Minatel|Oliver]]\n|{{Flagicon|England}} [[Jordan Brown (footballer, born 1996)|Jordan Brown]]\n|{{Flagicon|Peru|football}} [[Jair C\u00f3rdova]]\n|{{flagicon|England}} [[Nathan Mavila]]\n|{{flagicon|Honduras}} [[Jos\u00e9 Escalante]]\n|{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Richard Luca]]\n|\n|-\n|[[FC Edmonton]]\n|{{Flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[Kareem Moses]]\n|{{Flagicon|Spain}} [[Ram\u00f3n Soria]]\n|{{Flagicon|Cameroon}} [[Jeannot Esua]]\n|{{Flagicon|South Korea}} [[Son Yong-chan]]\n|{{Flagicon|Sweden}} [[Erik Zetterberg]]\n|{{Flagicon|Peru|football}} [[Ra\u00fal Tito]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Forge FC|Forge]]\n|{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Alexander Achinioti-J\u00f6nsson]]\n|{{flagicon|SEN}} [[Elimane Ciss\u00e9]]\n|{{flagicon|BEL}} [[Daniel Krutzen]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[HFX Wanderers FC|HFX Wanderers]] \n|{{Flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[Andre Rampersad]]\n|{{Flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[Akeem Garcia]]\n|{{Flagicon|Germany}} [[Peter Schaale]]\n|{{Flagicon|Jamaica}} [[Alex Marshall (footballer)|Alex Marshall]]\n|{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Eriks Santos]]\n|{{Flagicon|Brazil}} Jo\u00e3o Morelli\n|\n|-\n|[[Pacific FC|Pacific]]\n|{{Flagicon|Mexico}} [[Alejandro D\u00edaz Lice\u00e1ga|Alejandro D\u00edaz]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Valour FC|Valour]]\n|{{Flagicon|GHA}} Solomon Kojo Antwi\n|{{Flagicon|HAI}} [[Andrew Jean-Baptiste]]\n|{{Flagicon|PAN}} Amir Soto\n|{{Flagicon|NZL}} [[Moses Dyer]]\n|{{Flagicon|CGO}} [[Arnold Bouka Moutou]]\n|{{Flagicon|SPA}} [[Jos\u00e9 Gal\u00e1n]]\n|\n|-\n|[[York9 FC|York9]]\n|{{Flagicon|Japan}} [[Wataru Murofushi]]\n|{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Gabriel Vasconcelos (footballer, born 1996)|Gabriel Vasconcelos]]\n|{{Flagicon|Japan}} [[Fugo Segawa]]\n|{{Flagicon|Jamaica}} Nicholas Hamilton\n|{{Flagicon|Peru|football}} [[Adri\u00e1n Ugarriza]]\n|{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Jac\u00f3 (footballer)|Jac\u00f3]]\n|{{Flagicon|Argentina}} Brian L\u00f3pez\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2020 Canadian Championship]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n{{2020 Canadian Premier League season by team}}\n{{Canadian Premier League}}\n{{2020 in Canadian soccer}}\n{{2019\u201320 in North and Central America, and Caribbean football (CONCACAF)}}\n<!-- {{2020\u201321 in North and Central America, and Caribbean football (CONCACAF)|state=collapsed}}-->\n\n[[Category:2020 Canadian Premier League| ]]\n[[Category:Canadian Premier League seasons]]\n[[Category:2020 in Canadian soccer|Canadian Premier League]]\n[[Category:Sports events postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Canadian Premier League]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlayoff and finals:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: two round \u2192 two-round", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Canadian_Premier_League_season"}
{"title_page": "Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia", "text_new": "{{redirect-several|Ash Sharqiyah}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2012}}\n{{short description|Administrative region of Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Infobox state\n| name                            = Eastern Province\n| area_rank                       = 1\n| subdivision_type2               = Locality\n| subdivision_type3               = Municipalities\n| unit_pref                       = metric\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_as_of                = 2017\n| subdivision_type1               = Governorates\n| area_code                       = 013\n| postal_code                     = 3XXXX\n| utc_offset                      = +3\n| timezone1                       = [[Arabian Standard Time]]\n| iso_code                        = SA-04\n| population_rank                 = 3\n| official_name                   = al-Mintaqah ash-Sharqiyyah\n| population_total                = 4900325\n| area_total_km2                  = 672522\n| leader_name1                    = [[Ahmed bin Fahd bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Ahmed bin Fahd]]\n| leader_name                     = [[Saud bin Nayef Al Saud|Prince Saud bin Nayef]]\n| leader_title1                   = Deputy Governor\n| leader_title                    = Governor\n| image_map                       = Ash Sharqiyah in Saudi Arabia.svg\n| subdivision_name                = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| subdivision_type                = [[Country]]\n| settlement_type                 = [[State (polity)|State]]\n| seat                            = [[Dammam]]\n| seat_type                       = [[Capital city|Capital]]\n| native_name_lang                = ar\n| native_name                     = \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0637\u0642\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0642\u064a\u0629\n| parts_type                      = Governorates\n| p1                              = [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Ahsa Governorate]]<br>\n[[Dhahran|Dhahran Governorate]]<br>\n[[Khobar|Khobar Governorate]]<br>\n[[Qatif|Qatif Governorate]]<br>\n[[Hafar Al-Batin|Hafr al-Batin Governorate]]<br>\n[[Jubail|Jubail Governorate]]<br>\n[[Khafji|Khafji Governorate]]<br>\n[[Ras Tanura|Ra's Tanura Governorate]]<br>\n[[Abqaiq|Abqaiq Governorate]]<br>\n[[Al Nairyah|Na'iriyah Governorate]]<br>\n[[Qaryat al-Ulya|Qaryat al-Ulya Governorate]]\n}}\nThe '''Eastern Province''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0642\u064a\u0629}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|ash-Sharqiyyah}}'') is the easternmost of the 13 [[Provinces of saudi arabia|provinces]] of [[Saudi Arabia]]. It is the largest province of Saudi Arabia by area and the third most populous with a population of 4,900,325 as of 2017, after the [[Riyadh Province]] and the [[Makkah Province]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stats.gov.sa/sites/default/files/population_characteristics_surveysar.pdf|title=Population Characteristics surveys|date=2017|website=General Authority for Statistics}}</ref>. Of which 3,140,362 were Saudi citizens and 1,759,963 were foreign nationals <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/407209|title=Riyadh most populous Saudi city, Makkah most populous province|date=2012-02-25|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The province accounts for 10.05% of the entire population of Saudi Arabia<ref name=\":0\" /> and is named for its geographical location relative to the rest of the kingdom.\n\nMore than a third of the population is concentrated in the [[Greater Dammam|Dammam metropolitan area]]. With an estimated population of 1.25 million as of 2019,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrotrends.net/cities/22416/ad-dammam/population|title=Ad-Dammam, Saudi Arabia Population 1950-2020|website=www.macrotrends.net|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> [[Dammam]], the capital of the province, is the sixth most populous city in the kingdom. The incumbent governor of the province is [[Saud bin Nayef Al Saud|Prince Saud bin Nayef Al Saud]]. Other populous cities in the province include [[Hofuf]], Mubarraz, [[Hafar Al-Batin|Hafr al-Batin]], [[Jubail]] and [[Khobar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldpopulationreview.com/countries/saudi-arabia-population/cities/|website=worldpopulationreview.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. The region is extremely popular among tourists for its beaches on the [[Persian Gulf]] and proximity to the other countries of the eastern [[Arab world]], such as the [[UAE|United Arab Emirates]] and [[Bahrain]], with the latter being linked to the province via the 25 km (15 mi) long [[King Fahd Causeway]]. The region also shares a border with [[Oman]]. The province is bordered to the west, from north to south, by the provinces of the [[Northern Borders Region|Northern Borders]], [[Ha'il Region|Ha'il]], [[Al-Qassim Region|Qassim]], [[Riyadh Region|Riyadh]] and [[Najran Region|Najran]].\n\nThe Eastern Province encompasses the entire east coast of Saudi Arabia and acts as a major platform for most of the kingdom's oil production and exports. [[Petroleum|Oil]] was first found in the country in the Eastern Province, at the Prosperity Well site (formerly known as Dammam No.7). The [[Ghawar Field|Ghawar oil field]], located in the [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Ahsa Governorate]], measuring 8400 sq.km. (3240 sq.mi.) is the largest oil field in the world, and accounts for roughly a third of the kingdom's oil production. The [[Safaniya Oil Field|Safaniya oil field]], located off the coast of the province, is the largest [[offshore oil field]] in the world. The Jubail Industrial City, part of the city of [[Jubail]], the fifth most populous in the province, is the largest industrial city in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/world-s-largest-industrial-areas.html|title=The World's Largest Industrial Areas|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\nThe area was largely uninhabited until the [[Iron Age]], when a few people migrated over from the [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid]] and [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonian]] empires. For most of the early medieval period, the region was under [[Persian Empire|Persian]] and [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] rule until the advent of Islam under [[Muhammad]], and subsequently, the [[Islamic empires]] during the [[Islamic Golden Age]]. After a brief period of [[British Empire|British]] rule during the early modern period, the [[Unification of Saudi Arabia]] led to the consolidation of the region into the [[Kingdom of Hejaz and Nejd]], which in 1932, was united into the modern [[Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]].\n\n==Geography==\nApproximately two-thirds of the province is desert, comprising of, from south to north, the [[Rub' al Khali]], [[Ad-Dahna Desert|Dahna]] and [[An Nafud|Nafud]] deserts, with the Rub' al-Khali alone comprising more than half of the area of the province. Areas such as [[Hafar Al-Batin|Hafr al-Batin]] and the [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa Oasis]] have become important sites for [[desert farming]] due to the advancements made during the [[Green Revolution]] in farming and irrigation techniques. \n\nThe entire eastern coast of the kingdom lies in the Eastern Province. The region borders, from north to south, the countries of [[Iraq]], [[Kuwait]], [[Bahrain|Bahrain,]] [[Qatar]], [[United Arab Emirates]] and [[Oman]].\n\n==History==\n{{unsourced section|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Mohammad adil-Rashidun empire-slide.gif|thumb|335x335px|The [[Rashidun Caliphate]] expanded the Muslim world into three continents within 20 years of the death of [[Muhammad]]]]\n\n=== Lakhmid and Sasanian rule (300-623 AD) ===\nThe northern part of the Eastern Province was first inhabited by the [[Lakhmids]] around 300 AD, with the coastal regions claimed by the [[Sasanians]] but governed by the Lakhmids. Much of the Eastern Province was under [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] rule at the time of [[Muhammad|Muhammad.]] The entire [[Arabian Peninsula]] fell into Muslim hands during the [[Rashidun Caliphate]] and the [[Muslim conquest of Persia]], after [[Muhammad]]'s death. \n[[File:IbnSaud.jpg|thumb|[[King of Saudi Arabia|King]] [[Ibn Saud]] is largely accepted to be the founder of present-day [[Saudi Arabia]], also known as the Third Saudi State]]\n\n=== Rashidun, Umayyad and Abbasid caliphates (623-661, 661-750 & 750-899 AD) ===\nThe region stayed stable during the first three Islamic caliphates.\n\n=== Qarmatian rule (899-1076 AD) ===\nDuring the [[Abbasid Caliphate]], the region was taken over by the [[Qarmatians]], a [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] group of the [[Isma'ilism|Isma'ili]] branch, around 899 AD. The Qarmatians attacked [[Makkah]] and [[Madinah]] and held the [[Black Stone]] to ransom in Ahsa in 920 AD. The region was ruled by the Qaramatians until 976 AD, when after losing to the Abbasids, they were reduced to the status of a local power. After Bahrain and Qatif seceded from Qarmatian rule around 1058 AD, they retreated to the [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa Oasis]], to which [[Abdullah bin Ali Al Uyuni]] laid siege and invaded in 1076 AD, ending the rule of Qarmatians in Ahsa and founding the [[Uyunid Emirate]]. \n\n=== Uyunids, Usfurids and Jabrids (1076-1253, 1253-1320 & 1520-1521 AD) ===\nNot much is known of the Uyunids, except that they were the descendants of the [[Banu Abdul Qays]] tribe. They were involved in several internal disputes, causing the emirate to become unstable and eventually leading to the rise of the Bedouin Usfurids.\n\nThe Usfurids saw a short period of stability. After overthrowing their former allies, the Uyunids, they had an uneasy relationship with the Persian rulers of Hormuz, who took control of the former Uyunid cities of Qatif and Bahrain around 1320 AD. This eventually led to the fall of the Usfurids. \n\nThe region was mostly overlooked until 1520 AD, when the [[Jabrids]] built a more stable [[polity]], only for it to fall just a year later, in 1521.\n\n=== Ottoman invasions (1551-1671 AD) ===\nIn 1551 AD, the Ottomans invaded the region during their [[Ottoman-Safavid War (1532-1555)|first war with the Safavids]], and kept it under their control until 1671.\n\nThe region has stayed in Muslims hands since. In the late 1800s, during the period of the [[Second Saudi State]], the area came into Saudi control for the first time from Ottoman hands, before briefly being taken over by the [[Ottoman Empire]] and then retaken by the [[Kingdom of Hejaz and Nejd]] after the in 1913, which was later consolidated into the modern [[Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] under [[Ibn Saud]] on September 23, 1932.\n\nDue to the significance of the [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa Oasis]], the region around the oasis, which comprises much of modern-day [[Hofuf]] and its surrounding areas, was simply known as ''al-Ahsa''' and the region around present-day [[Bahrain]] and the [[Greater Dammam]] area was simply known as ''al-Bahran'' from pre-Islamic times.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2015}}According to the Population Characteristics Surveys conducted by the General Authority of Statistics, the Eastern Province had a population of 4,900,325 as of December 2017<ref name=\":0\" />, of which 3,140,362 were Saudis and 1,759,963 were foreign nationals. The Eastern Province is the third most populous province in Saudi Arabia, after Makkah and Riyadh. With an estimated population of 1,225,000 as of 2019<ref name=\":1\" />, Dammam is the most populous city in the province and the sixth most populous city in the country. \n\n===Religion===\n{{Main|Religion in Saudi Arabia}}\nCensuses in Saudi Arabia do not collect or report data regarding religion. [[Sunni Islam]] of the [[Hanbali]] school of [[Islamic jurisprudence]] is the predominant religion overall in the country, with smaller numbers of [[Hanafi|Hanafis]], [[Shafi\u2018i|Shafi\u2018is]] and [[Maliki|Malikis]]. [[Shia Islam|Shia]] Muslims are highly localized in some areas of the Eastern Province, particularly in [[Qatif]].<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629: \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0647\u0645\u064a\u0634 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u062d\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0621|url=http://arabic.cnn.com/2007/middle_east/3/8/shiite-saudi/}}</ref> An extremely small number of [[Hindus]], [[Christians]] and other religious groups does exist, most of whom are [[Expatriate|expatriates]] from [[India]] and the [[Philippines]].\n\n===Languages===\nThe official language of Saudi Arabia is [[Arabic]]. The three main regional dialects spoken by Saudis are [[Hejazi Arabic]],<ref>[[:ethnologue:acw|Arabic, Hijazi Spoken]]. Ethnologue</ref> [[Najdi Arabic]],<ref>[[:ethnologue:ars|Arabic, Najdi Spoken]]. Ethnologue</ref> and [[Gulf Arabic]].<ref>[[:ethnologue:afb|Arabic, Gulf Spoken]]. Ethnologue</ref> There are approximately 2 million Gulf Arabic speakers in Saudi Arabia, and the dialect is only spoken in the Eastern Province.<ref name=\"ksa\"/> The remaining Arabic speakers in the province speak one of the other two dialects, more commonly the Najdi dialect.<ref name=ksa>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sl_dDVctycgC&pg=RA3-PA38&d&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TOzdUePFGYzLtAaZmYGwBg&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=International Encyclopedia of Linguistics, Volume 1 |work= William Frawley |date= 2003 |pages=38}}</ref><ref name=per>[http://www.ethnologue.com/country/sa/languages Languages of Saudi Arabia] ''[[Ethnologue]]''</ref> [[Saudi Sign Language]] is the principal language of the deaf community.  The large expatriate communities also speak their own languages, the most numerous of which are [[Languages of India|Indian languages]], [[Filipino language|Filipino]]/[[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Urdu]].<ref name=\"HRW\">{{citation|chapter=Migrant Communities in Saudi Arabia|title=Bad Dreams: Exploitation and Abuse of Migrant Workers in Saudi Arabia|year=2004|publisher=Human Rights Watch|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2004/saudi0704%7c/4.htm#_Toc75678056}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=SA Saudi Arabia]. Ethnologue</ref>\n\n==Governors==\n* [[Abdallah bin Jiluwi|Abdullah bin Jalawi]] (1912-1935)\n* Saud bin Abdullah bin Jalawi Al Saud (1935-1967)\n* Abdul Muhsin bin Abdullah Al Jalawi (1967-1985)\n* [[Muhammad bin Fahd]] (1985-2013)\n* [[Saud bin Nayef]] (2013\u2013present)\n\n==Economy==\nThe economy of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia is largely dependent on oil. As such, the Eastern Province, being the province with most of Saudi Arabia's oil reserves enjoys a high economic position. [[Saudi Aramco]], the [[government-owned corporation|state-owned]] oil company of Saudi Arabia and an organization of major significance in the [[petroleum industry]], is based in [[Dhahran]] in [[Greater Dammam]]. It became the fifth company in the world to reach a [[market capitalization]] of $1 trillion ($1,000,000,000,000) on December 11, 2019. After going public the same day in what is considered the largest [[IPO|public offering]] ever as of December 2019, the next day, on December 12, 2019, the company reached a market cap of $2 trillion, becoming the first and only company in the world to break the record. The kingdom's main oil and gas fields are located in the Eastern Province with sites such as the [[Ghawar Field]], the largest onshore [[Petroleum reservoir|oil field]] in the world and the [[Safaniya Oil Field|Safaniya oil field]], the largest offshore oil field in the world. Petroleum from the fields is shipped to dozens of countries from the port cities of [[Ras Tanura|Ra's Tanura]] and [[Jeddah]].\n\nSaudi Arabia's largest agricultural product, dates, also forms a large part of the province's economy. Every year thousands of tonnes of dates are harvested from the date palms in the giant oasis of [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa]].\n\nThe same as other cities in the Kingdom the area has faced reasonable growth over the past two years; however, it has always maintained a more consistent real estate progress due to the smaller number of major projects that can affect its real estate landscape and due the long term outlook of many firms located within it. A D Williams indicated in the Saudi Real Estate Companion that despite being home to some of the largest conglomerates in the region, namely [[Saudi Aramco|Aramco]] and [[SABIC|Sabic]], the Eastern Province did fall behind the rest of the country when it came to non-oil related services.\n\n==Transportation==\nDammam's [[King Fahd International Airport]], the largest airport in the world in terms of land area, is the only airport in the entire Eastern Province with scheduled international flights. Located 30&nbsp;km northwest of the city, the airport is the primary air hub of the Eastern Province. Dammam is well connected by air with other cities in the Middle East, Asia, and Europe. Other airports in the province include [[Al-Ahsa International Airport|Ahsa International Airport]] and [[Al Qaisumah/Hafr Al Batin Airport|Qaisumah-Hafr Al Batin Airport]].\n\nThe [[King Abdul Aziz Port|King Abdulaziz Sea Port]], located on the coast of the [[Persian Gulf]], is the second largest and second busiest port in [[Saudi Arabia]]. It is also the largest port in the Persian Gulf and was built in the 1940s. The port is equipped with 56 multi-purpose hoists, 8 container cranes, and 524 tanker containers.\n\nHighway 95 (Route 5M) connects [[Khafji]] on the [[Kuwait|Kuwaiti]] border in the north to the Ramlah border station on the [[Oman|Omani]] border in the south via [[Jubail]], [[Ras Tanura|Ra's Tanura]], the [[Dammam metropolitan area]], the Salwa border station on the [[Qatar|Qatari]] border and the Batha' border station with the [[United Arab Emirates]]. Highway 40 (Route 80M) connects [[Bahrain]] and [[Dammam]] via the 25 km (15 mi) [[King Fahd Causeway]] over the [[Persian Gulf]] and onward to [[Jeddah]] on the [[Red Sea]] via [[Riyadh]], [[Ta'if]] and [[Makkah]].\n\nIntercity bus services are operated in the province by the Saudi Arabian Public Transport Company (SAPTCO). [[Umrah]] and [[Hajj]] shuttle services are also provided to residents of the kingdom by private contractors. Shuttle services also connect the [[Dammam metropolitan area]] to the [[Bahrain International Airport]], northeast of [[Manama]] in Bahrain.\n\nA plan to build a [[Dammam Metro|metro]] in Dammam is also in the works.\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n{{see also|Regions of Saudi Arabia|List of governorates of Saudi Arabia}}\nThe Eastern Province is one of the 13 [[regions of Saudi Arabia]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arab.net/saudi/sa_admindivisions.htm |title=Saudi Arabia: Administrative divisions |publisher=arab.net }}</ref> ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0637\u0642 \u0625\u062f\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629}}; ''manatiq id\u0101riyya'', sing. \u0645\u0646\u0637\u0642\u0629 \u0625\u062f\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629; ''[[mintaqah]] idariyya''). The region is further subdivided into 11 [[Governorates of Saudi Arabia|governorates]] ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0627\u0641\u0638\u0627\u062a}}; ''muhafazat'', sing. \u0645\u062d\u0627\u0641\u0638\u0629; ''[[muhafazah]]''). The governorates are further sudivided into sub-governorates ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0643\u0632}}; ''[[Markaz (country subdivision)|marakiz]]'', sing. \u0645\u0631\u0643\u0632; ''markaz'').\n\nThe Eastern Province's capital city of Dammam has special status. Like the other 12 regional capitals, Dammam is not included within any governorate but is instead governed by a \"municipality\" ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0629}}; ''amanah'') headed by a [[mayor]] ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646}}; ''amin''). The [[Al-Ahsa Governorate]], which includes the traditional oasis of [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Al-Hasa]] and the [[Rub' al Khali]] desert, is the largest governorate in Saudi Arabia in terms of area.\n\n=== List of governorates ===\n* [[Abqaiq]] ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0642\u064a\u0642}})\n* [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Ahsa]] ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0621}})\n* [[Dhahran]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0638\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646}})\n* [[Hafar Al-Batin]] ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0627\u0637\u0646}})\n* [[Jubail]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644}})\n* [[Khafji]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0641\u062c\u064a}})\n* [[Khobar]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0628\u0631}})\n* [[Nariyah]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0639\u064a\u0631\u064a\u0629}})\n* [[Qaryat al-Ulya]] ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0627}})\n* [[Qatif]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0637\u064a\u0641}})\n* [[Ras Tanura]] ({{lang|ar|\u0631\u0623\u0633 \u062a\u0646\u0648\u0631\u0629}})\n\n=== List of sub-governorates ===\n* Markaz al Musannah\n* Markaz al 'Udayd\n\n=== Major cities ===\n* [[Dammam]]: Capital of Eastern Province, the main seaport and the fifth largest city of Saudi Arabia (after [[Riyadh]], [[Jeddah]], [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]]).\n* [[Khobar]]: Major city in Eastern Province and center for commerce.\n* [[Dhahran]]: Oil industry center, site of [[Saudi Aramco]] headquarters. Its home to a major base of [[Royal Saudi Air Force]] and the most prestigious Saudi university, [[KFUPM]]. \n* [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Al-Hasa]]: Largest oasis in the world. Al-Hasa is sometimes considered by the people of the province to be a province by itself, since it has its own annual budget and its own local government, unlike the other areas in the province. The local government is formally known as the Al-Ahsa Governorate, a division of the Government of the Eastern Province. In addition, Al-Hasa has a mayor who has a power of a governor, although not \"officially\" considered as a governor because the province's governor still can control the operation of Al-Hasa Governorate and its mayor's office. Nonetheless, the Eastern Province's governor is still considered the head of the province government in any local occasion that occurs in Al-Hasa.\n* [[Qatif]]: Large oasis on the coast of the [[Persian Gulf]]\n* [[Jubail]]: Largest industrial city in the [[Middle East]].\n* [[Abqaiq]]: Home for major and largest oil and gas processing plants\n* [[Ras Tanura]]: Major petroleum refining center, home for the largest oil refinery in the world, and many [[Oil platform|offshore oil platforms]]. Also main oil exporting seaport\n* [[Udhailiyah]]: Major oil producing and processing plants\n* [[Shayba]] in the [[Rub' al Khali]] (Empty Quarter), close to the border with the [[United Arab Emirates]]\n* [[Khafji]]: Main industrial city, very close to the border with [[Kuwait]]. Occupied by the Iraqi forces during the [[Gulf War]]. Saudi Forces aided by [[United States]] [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]] victoriously engaged in the [[Battle of Khafji]] during [[Operation Desert Storm]] to free it from the Iraqis.\n* [[Hafar Al-Batin]]: The largest city in the North-East of Saudi Arabia, it is 90&nbsp;km near [[Kuwait]] and it has more than 35 villages. [[King Khalid Military City]] is 60&nbsp;km South to it.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n* [[Bahrain (historical region)]]\n* [[List of cities and towns in Saudi Arabia]]\n* [[Regions of Saudi Arabia]]\n* [[Shi'a Islam in Saudi Arabia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}<br />{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Eastern Province\n| North     = {{flagicon|Kuwait}}[[Al Jahra Governorate|Al Jahra]] and [[Al Ahmadi Governorate|Al Ahmadi]] governorates, [[Kuwait]]\n| Northeast = {{flagicon|Bahrain}} [[Bahrain]]\n| East      = {{flagicon|Qatar}}[[Jariyan al Batnah]], [[Qatar]]<br>{{flagicon|UAE}}[[Abu Dhabi (emirate)|Abu Dhabi]], [[UAE]]\n| Southeast = {{flagicon|Oman}}[[Ad Dhahirah Governorate|Ad Dhahirah]], [[Al Wusta Governorate (Oman)|Al Wusta]], and [[Dhofar Governorate|Dhofar]] Governorates , [[Oman]]\n| South     = {{flagicon|Yemen}}[[Hadhramaut Governorate]], [[Yemen]]\n| Southwest = [[Najran Region]]\n| West      = [[Riyadh Region]]\n| Northwest = {{flagicon|Iraq}}[[Al Muthanna Governorate]], [[Iraq]]<br>[[Northern Borders Region]]\n}}\n\n{{Regions of Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Saudi Arabia topics}}\n{{Saudi cities}}\n\n[[Category:Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia| ]]\n[[Category:Geography of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Saudi Arabia]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect-several|Ash Sharqiyah}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2012}}\n{{short description|Administrative region of Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Infobox state\n| name                            = Eastern Province\n| area_rank                       = 1\n| subdivision_type2               = Locality\n| subdivision_type3               = Municipalities\n| unit_pref                       = metric\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_as_of                = 2017\n| subdivision_type1               = Governorates\n| area_code                       = 013\n| postal_code                     = 3XXXX\n| utc_offset                      = +3\n| timezone1                       = [[Arabian Standard Time]]\n| iso_code                        = SA-04\n| population_rank                 = 3\n| official_name                   = al-Mintaqah ash-Sharqiyyah\n| population_total                = 4900325\n| area_total_km2                  = 672522\n| leader_name1                    = [[Ahmed bin Fahd bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Ahmed bin Fahd]]\n| leader_name                     = [[Saud bin Nayef Al Saud|Prince Saud bin Nayef]]\n| leader_title1                   = Deputy Governor\n| leader_title                    = Governor\n| image_map                       = Ash Sharqiyah in Saudi Arabia.svg\n| subdivision_name                = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| subdivision_type                = [[Country]]\n| settlement_type                 = [[State (polity)|State]]\n| seat                            = [[Dammam]]\n| seat_type                       = [[Capital city|Capital]]\n| native_name_lang                = ar\n| native_name                     = \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u0637\u0642\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0642\u064a\u0629\n| parts_type                      = Governorates\n| p1                              = [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Ahsa Governorate]]<br>\n[[Dhahran|Dhahran Governorate]]<br>\n[[Khobar|Khobar Governorate]]<br>\n[[Qatif|Qatif Governorate]]<br>\n[[Hafar Al-Batin|Hafr al-Batin Governorate]]<br>\n[[Jubail|Jubail Governorate]]<br>\n[[Khafji|Khafji Governorate]]<br>\n[[Ras Tanura|Ra's Tanura Governorate]]<br>\n[[Abqaiq|Abqaiq Governorate]]<br>\n[[Al Nairyah|Na'iriyah Governorate]]<br>\n[[Qaryat al-Ulya|Qaryat al-Ulya Governorate]]\n}}\nThe '''Eastern Province''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0642\u064a\u0629}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|ash-Sharqiyyah}}'') is the easternmost of the 13 [[Provinces of saudi arabia|provinces]] of [[Saudi Arabia]]. It is the largest province of Saudi Arabia by area and the third most populous with a population of 4,900,325 as of 2017, after the [[Riyadh Province]] and the [[Makkah Province]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stats.gov.sa/sites/default/files/population_characteristics_surveysar.pdf|title=Population Characteristics surveys|date=2017|website=General Authority for Statistics}}</ref>. Of which 3,140,362 were Saudi citizens and 1,759,963 were foreign nationals <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/407209|title=Riyadh most populous Saudi city, Makkah most populous province|date=2012-02-25|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The province accounts for 10.05% of the entire population of Saudi Arabia<ref name=\":0\" /> and is named for its geographical location relative to the rest of the kingdom.\n\nMore than a third of the population is concentrated in the [[Greater Dammam|Dammam metropolitan area]]. With an estimated population of 1.25 million as of 2019,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrotrends.net/cities/22416/ad-dammam/population|title=Ad-Dammam, Saudi Arabia Population 1950-2020|website=www.macrotrends.net|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> [[Dammam]], the capital of the province, is the sixth most populous city in the kingdom. The incumbent governor of the province is [[Saud bin Nayef Al Saud|Prince Saud bin Nayef Al Saud]]. Other populous cities in the province include [[Hofuf]], Mubarraz, [[Hafar Al-Batin|Hafr al-Batin]], [[Jubail]] and [[Khobar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldpopulationreview.com/countries/saudi-arabia-population/cities/|website=worldpopulationreview.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. The region is extremely popular among tourists for its beaches on the [[Persian Gulf]] and proximity to the other countries of the eastern [[Arab world]], such as the [[UAE|United Arab Emirates]] and [[Bahrain]], with the latter being linked to the province via the 25 km (15 mi) long [[King Fahd Causeway]]. The region also shares a border with [[Oman]]. The province is bordered to the west, from north to south, by the provinces of the [[Northern Borders Region|Northern Borders]], [[Ha'il Region|Ha'il]], [[Al-Qassim Region|Qassim]], [[Riyadh Region|Riyadh]] and [[Najran Region|Najran]].\n\nThe Eastern Province encompasses the entire east coast of Saudi Arabia and acts as a major platform for most of the kingdom's oil production and exports. [[Petroleum|Oil]] was first found in the country in the Eastern Province, at the Prosperity Well site (formerly known as Dammam No.7). The [[Ghawar Field|Ghawar oil field]], located in the [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Ahsa Governorate]], measuring 8400 sq.km. (3240 sq.mi.) is the largest oil field in the world, and accounts for roughly a third of the kingdom's oil production. The [[Safaniya Oil Field|Safaniya oil field]], located off the coast of the province, is the largest [[offshore oil field]] in the world. The Jubail Industrial City, part of the city of [[Jubail]], the fifth most populous in the province, is the largest industrial city in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/world-s-largest-industrial-areas.html|title=The World's Largest Industrial Areas|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\nThe area was largely uninhabited until the [[Iron Age]], when a few people migrated over from the [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid]] and [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonian]] empires. For most of the early medieval period, the region was under [[Persian Empire|Persian]] and [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] rule until the advent of Islam under [[Muhammad]], and subsequently, the [[Islamic empires]] during the [[Islamic Golden Age]]. After a brief period of [[British Empire|British]] rule during the early modern period, the [[Unification of Saudi Arabia]] led to the consolidation of the region into the [[Kingdom of Hejaz and Nejd]], which in 1932, was united into the modern [[Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]].\n\n==Geography==\nApproximately two-thirds of the province is desert, comprising of, from south to north, the [[Rub' al Khali]], [[Ad-Dahna Desert|Dahna]] and [[An Nafud|Nafud]] deserts, with the Rub' al-Khali alone comprising more than half of the area of the province. Areas such as [[Hafar Al-Batin|Hafr al-Batin]] and the [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa Oasis]] have become important sites for [[desert farming]] due to the advancements made during the [[Green Revolution]] in farming and irrigation techniques. \n\nThe entire eastern coast of the kingdom lies in the Eastern Province. The region borders, from north to south, the countries of [[Iraq]], [[Kuwait]], [[Bahrain|Bahrain,]] [[Qatar]], [[United Arab Emirates]] and [[Oman]].\n\n==History==\n{{unsourced section|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Mohammad adil-Rashidun empire-slide.gif|thumb|335x335px|The [[Rashidun Caliphate]] expanded the Muslim world into three continents within 20 years of the death of [[Muhammad]]]]\n\n=== Lakhmid and Sasanian rule (300-623 AD) ===\nThe northern part of the Eastern Province was first inhabited by the [[Lakhmids]] around 300 AD, with the coastal regions claimed by the [[Sasanians]] but governed by the Lakhmids. Much of the Eastern Province was under [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] rule at the time of [[Muhammad|Muhammad.]] The entire [[Arabian Peninsula]] fell into Muslim hands during the [[Rashidun Caliphate]] and the [[Muslim conquest of Persia]], after [[Muhammad]]'s death. \n[[File:IbnSaud.jpg|thumb|[[King of Saudi Arabia|King]] [[Ibn Saud]] is largely accepted to be the founder of present-day [[Saudi Arabia]], also known as the Third Saudi State]]\n\n=== Rashidun, Umayyad and Abbasid caliphates (623-661, 661-750 & 750-899 AD) ===\nThe region stayed stable during the first three Islamic caliphates.\n\n=== Qarmatian rule (899-1076 AD) ===\nDuring the [[Abbasid Caliphate]], the region was taken over by the [[Qarmatians]], a [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] group of the [[Isma'ilism|Isma'ili]] branch, around 899 AD. The Qarmatians attacked [[Makkah]] and [[Madinah]] and held the [[Black Stone]] to ransom in Ahsa in 920 AD. The region was ruled by the Qaramatians until 976 AD, when after losing to the Abbasids, they were reduced to the status of a local power. After Bahrain and Qatif seceded from Qarmatian rule around 1058 AD, they retreated to the [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa Oasis]], to which [[Abdullah bin Ali Al Uyuni]] laid siege and invaded in 1076 AD, ending the rule of Qarmatians in Ahsa and founding the [[Uyunid Emirate]]. \n\n=== Uyunids, Usfurids and Jabrids (1076-1253, 1253-1320 & 1520-1521 AD) ===\nNot much is known of the Uyunids, except that they were the descendants of the [[Banu Abdul Qays]] tribe. They were involved in several internal disputes, causing the emirate to become unstable and eventually leading to the rise of the Bedouin Usfurids.\n\nThe Usfurids saw a short period of stability. After overthrowing their former allies, the Uyunids, they had an uneasy relationship with the Persian rulers of Hormuz, who took control of the former Uyunid cities of Qatif and Bahrain around 1320 AD. This eventually led to the fall of the Usfurids. \n\nThe region was mostly overlooked until 1520 AD, when the [[Jabrids]] built a more stable [[polity]], only for it to fall just a year later, in 1521.\n\n=== Ottoman invasions (1551-1671 AD) ===\nIn 1551 AD, the Ottomans invaded the region during their [[Ottoman-Safavid War (1532-1555)|first war with the Safavids]], and kept it under their control until 1671.\n\nThe region has stayed in Muslims hands since. In the late 1800s, during the period of the [[Second Saudi State]], the area came into Saudi control for the first time from Ottoman hands, before briefly being taken over by the [[Ottoman Empire]] and then retaken by the [[Kingdom of Hejaz and Nejd]] after the in 1913, which was later consolidated into the modern [[Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] under [[Ibn Saud]] on September 23, 1932.\n\nDue to the significance of the [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa Oasis]], the region around the oasis, which comprises much of modern-day [[Hofuf]] and its surrounding areas, was simply known as ''al-Ahsa''' and the region around present-day [[Bahrain]] and the [[Greater Dammam]] area was simply known as ''al-Bahran'' from pre-Islamic times.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2015}}{{historical populations|11=1992|12=2,575,820|13=2004|14=3,360,031|15=2010|16=4,130,033|17=2018|18=5,028,753|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.citypopulation.de/en/saudiarabia/cities/ Saudi Arabia: Regions and Cities]</ref>|align=right}}According to the Population Characteristics Surveys conducted by the General Authority of Statistics, the Eastern Province had a population of 4,900,325 as of December 2017<ref name=\":0\" />, of which 3,140,362 were Saudis and 1,759,963 were foreign nationals. The Eastern Province is the third most populous province in Saudi Arabia, after Makkah and Riyadh. With an estimated population of 1,225,000 as of 2019<ref name=\":1\" />, Dammam is the most populous city in the province and the sixth most populous city in the country. \n\n===Religion===\n{{Main|Religion in Saudi Arabia}}\nCensuses in Saudi Arabia do not collect or report data regarding religion. [[Sunni Islam]] of the [[Hanbali]] school of [[Islamic jurisprudence]] is the predominant religion overall in the country, with smaller numbers of [[Hanafi|Hanafis]], [[Shafi\u2018i|Shafi\u2018is]] and [[Maliki|Malikis]]. [[Shia Islam|Shia]] Muslims are highly localized in some areas of the Eastern Province, particularly in [[Qatif]].<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a\u0629: \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0647\u0645\u064a\u0634 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u062d\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0621|url=http://arabic.cnn.com/2007/middle_east/3/8/shiite-saudi/}}</ref> An extremely small number of [[Hindus]], [[Christians]] and other religious groups does exist, most of whom are [[Expatriate|expatriates]] from [[India]] and the [[Philippines]].\n\n===Languages===\nThe official language of Saudi Arabia is [[Arabic]]. The three main regional dialects spoken by Saudis are [[Hejazi Arabic]],<ref>[[:ethnologue:acw|Arabic, Hijazi Spoken]]. Ethnologue</ref> [[Najdi Arabic]],<ref>[[:ethnologue:ars|Arabic, Najdi Spoken]]. Ethnologue</ref> and [[Gulf Arabic]].<ref>[[:ethnologue:afb|Arabic, Gulf Spoken]]. Ethnologue</ref> There are approximately 2 million Gulf Arabic speakers in Saudi Arabia, and the dialect is only spoken in the Eastern Province.<ref name=\"ksa\"/> The remaining Arabic speakers in the province speak one of the other two dialects, more commonly the Najdi dialect.<ref name=ksa>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sl_dDVctycgC&pg=RA3-PA38&d&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TOzdUePFGYzLtAaZmYGwBg&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=International Encyclopedia of Linguistics, Volume 1 |work= William Frawley |date= 2003 |pages=38}}</ref><ref name=per>[http://www.ethnologue.com/country/sa/languages Languages of Saudi Arabia] ''[[Ethnologue]]''</ref> [[Saudi Sign Language]] is the principal language of the deaf community.  The large expatriate communities also speak their own languages, the most numerous of which are [[Languages of India|Indian languages]], [[Filipino language|Filipino]]/[[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Urdu]].<ref name=\"HRW\">{{citation|chapter=Migrant Communities in Saudi Arabia|title=Bad Dreams: Exploitation and Abuse of Migrant Workers in Saudi Arabia|year=2004|publisher=Human Rights Watch|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2004/saudi0704%7c/4.htm#_Toc75678056}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=SA Saudi Arabia]. Ethnologue</ref>\n\n==Governors==\n* [[Abdallah bin Jiluwi]] (1912-1935)\n* Saud bin Abdullah bin Jalawi Al Saud (1935-1967)\n* Abdul Muhsin bin Abdullah Al Jiluw (1967-1985)\n* [[Muhammad bin Fahd]] (1985-2013)\n* [[Saud bin Nayef]] (2013\u2013present)\n\n==Economy==\nThe economy of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia is largely dependent on oil. As such, the Eastern Province, being the province with most of Saudi Arabia's oil reserves enjoys a high economic position. [[Saudi Aramco]], the [[government-owned corporation|state-owned]] oil company of Saudi Arabia and an organization of major significance in the [[petroleum industry]], is based in [[Dhahran]] in [[Greater Dammam]]. It became the fifth company in the world to reach a [[market capitalization]] of $1 trillion ($1,000,000,000,000) on December 11, 2019. After going public the same day in what is considered the largest [[IPO|public offering]] ever as of December 2019, the next day, on December 12, 2019, the company reached a market cap of $2 trillion, becoming the first and only company in the world to break the record. The kingdom's main oil and gas fields are located in the Eastern Province with sites such as the [[Ghawar Field]], the largest onshore [[Petroleum reservoir|oil field]] in the world and the [[Safaniya Oil Field|Safaniya oil field]], the largest offshore oil field in the world. Petroleum from the fields is shipped to dozens of countries from the port cities of [[Ras Tanura|Ra's Tanura]] and [[Jeddah]].\n\nSaudi Arabia's largest agricultural product, dates, also forms a large part of the province's economy. Every year thousands of tonnes of dates are harvested from the date palms in the giant oasis of [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Ahsa]].\n\nThe same as other cities in the Kingdom the area has faced reasonable growth over the past two years; however, it has always maintained a more consistent real estate progress due to the smaller number of major projects that can affect its real estate landscape and due the long term outlook of many firms located within it. A D Williams indicated in the Saudi Real Estate Companion that despite being home to some of the largest conglomerates in the region, namely [[Saudi Aramco|Aramco]] and [[SABIC|Sabic]], the Eastern Province did fall behind the rest of the country when it came to non-oil related services.\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Air===\nDammam's [[King Fahd International Airport]], the largest airport in the world in terms of land area. The passenger terminal is about 20&nbsp;km to the northwest of the city and is connected by a 6-lane highway. The airport is the primary air hub of the Eastern Province. Dammam is well connected by air with other cities in the Middle East, Asia, and Europe.\n\nOther international airports in the province are [[Al-Ahsa International Airport]] and [[Al Qaisumah/Hafr Al Batin Airport]].\n\n===Sea===\nThe [[King Abdul Aziz Port|King Abdul Aziz Sea Port]], located on the coast of the [[Persian Gulf]], is the second largest and second busiest port in [[Saudi Arabia]]. It is also the largest port in the Persian Gulf. It was founded in the late 1940s. It has large equipment that allows it to receive various types of vessels. The most important equipments are 56 multi-purpose hoist, 8 container cranes, and 524 tanker containers. There are a number of berths for ships and fishing, as well as ship repair yard.\n\n===Road===\nThe major cities of the Eastern Province cities such as [[Abqaiq]], [[Dammam]], [[Dhahran]], [[Hofuf]], [[Jubail]], [[Khafji]], [[Khobar]], [[Ras Tanura]], Sihat and [[Qatif]] ([[Gulf Road|Gulf Road (Saudi Arabia)]]) are well connected by highways. Dammam is connected to the Saudi capital, [[Riyadh]] and [[Jeddah]] on the west coast by [[Highway 40 (Saudi Arabia)|Highway 40]]. The Eastern Province is also linked to [[Bahrain]] by the 28&nbsp;km long [[King Fahd Causeway]], and to other Middle-Eastern countries such as [[Kuwait]] ([[Abu Hadriyah Highway]]), [[Oman]], [[Qatar]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]].\n\nInter-city bus services are operated in the province by the [[Saudi Arabian Public Transport Company]] (SAPTCO). Bus services also connect Dammam and other cities in Saudi Arabia, and across the Middle East.\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n{{see also|Regions of Saudi Arabia|List of governorates of Saudi Arabia}}\nThe Eastern Province is one of the 13 [[regions of Saudi Arabia]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arab.net/saudi/sa_admindivisions.htm |title=Saudi Arabia: Administrative divisions |publisher=arab.net }}</ref> ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0637\u0642 \u0625\u062f\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629}}; ''manatiq id\u0101riyya'', sing. \u0645\u0646\u0637\u0642\u0629 \u0625\u062f\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629; ''[[mintaqah]] idariyya''). The region is further subdivided into 11 [[Governorates of Saudi Arabia|governorates]] ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0627\u0641\u0638\u0627\u062a}}; ''muhafazat'', sing. \u0645\u062d\u0627\u0641\u0638\u0629; ''[[muhafazah]]''). The governorates are further sudivided into sub-governorates ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0643\u0632}}; ''[[Markaz (country subdivision)|marakiz]]'', sing. \u0645\u0631\u0643\u0632; ''markaz'').\n\nThe Eastern Province's capital city of Dammam has special status. Like the other 12 regional capitals, Dammam is not included within any governorate but is instead governed by a \"municipality\" ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0629}}; ''amanah'') headed by a [[mayor]] ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646}}; ''amin''). The [[Al-Ahsa Governorate]], which includes the traditional oasis of [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Al-Hasa]] and the [[Rub' al Khali]] desert, is the largest governorate in Saudi Arabia in terms of area.\n\n=== List of governorates ===\n* [[Abqaiq]] ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0642\u064a\u0642}})\n* [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|Al-Ahsa]] ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0621}})\n* [[Dhahran]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0638\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0646}})\n* [[Hafar Al-Batin]] ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0627\u0637\u0646}})\n* [[Jubail]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0628\u064a\u0644}})\n* [[Khafji]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0641\u062c\u064a}})\n* [[Khobar]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0628\u0631}})\n* [[Nariyah]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0639\u064a\u0631\u064a\u0629}})\n* [[Qaryat al-Ulya]] ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0627}})\n* [[Qatif]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0637\u064a\u0641}})\n* [[Ras Tanura]] ({{lang|ar|\u0631\u0623\u0633 \u062a\u0646\u0648\u0631\u0629}})\n\n=== List of sub-governorates ===\n* Markaz al Musannah\n* Markaz al 'Udayd\n\n=== Major cities ===\n* [[Dammam]]: Capital of Eastern Province, the main seaport and the fifth largest city of Saudi Arabia (after [[Riyadh]], [[Jeddah]], [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]]).\n* [[Khobar]]: Major city in Eastern Province and center for commerce.\n* [[Dhahran]]: Oil industry center, site of [[Saudi Aramco]] headquarters. Its home to a major base of [[Royal Saudi Air Force]] and the most prestigious Saudi university, [[KFUPM]]. \n* [[Al-Ahsa Oasis|Al-Hasa]]: Largest oasis in the world. Al-Hasa is sometimes considered by the people of the province to be a province by itself, since it has its own annual budget and its own local government, unlike the other areas in the province. The local government is formally known as the Al-Ahsa Governorate, a division of the Government of the Eastern Province. In addition, Al-Hasa has a mayor who has a power of a governor, although not \"officially\" considered as a governor because the province's governor still can control the operation of Al-Hasa Governorate and its mayor's office. Nonetheless, the Eastern Province's governor is still considered the head of the province government in any local occasion that occurs in Al-Hasa.\n* [[Qatif]]: Large oasis on the coast of the [[Persian Gulf]]\n* [[Jubail]]: Largest industrial city in the [[Middle East]].\n* [[Abqaiq]]: Home for major and largest oil and gas processing plants\n* [[Ras Tanura]]: Major petroleum refining center, home for the largest oil refinery in the world, and many [[Oil platform|offshore oil platforms]]. Also main oil exporting seaport\n* [[Udhailiyah]]: Major oil producing and processing plants\n* [[Shayba]] in the [[Rub' al Khali]] (Empty Quarter), close to the border with the [[United Arab Emirates]]\n* [[Khafji]]: Main industrial city, very close to the border with [[Kuwait]]. Occupied by the Iraqi forces during the [[Gulf War]]. Saudi Forces aided by [[United States]] [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]] victoriously engaged in the [[Battle of Khafji]] during [[Operation Desert Storm]] to free it from the Iraqis.\n* [[Hafar Al-Batin]]: The largest city in the North-East of Saudi Arabia, it is 90&nbsp;km near [[Kuwait]] and it has more than 35 villages. [[King Khalid Military City]] is 60&nbsp;km South to it.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n* [[Bahrain (historical region)]]\n* [[List of cities and towns in Saudi Arabia]]\n* [[Regions of Saudi Arabia]]\n* [[Shi'a Islam in Saudi Arabia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}<br />{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Eastern Province\n| North     = {{flagicon|Kuwait}}[[Al Jahra Governorate|Al Jahra]] and [[Al Ahmadi Governorate|Al Ahmadi]] governorates, [[Kuwait]]\n| Northeast = {{flagicon|Bahrain}} [[Bahrain]]\n| East      = {{flagicon|Qatar}}[[Jariyan al Batnah]], [[Qatar]]<br>{{flagicon|UAE}}[[Abu Dhabi (emirate)|Abu Dhabi]], [[UAE]]\n| Southeast = {{flagicon|Oman}}[[Ad Dhahirah Governorate|Ad Dhahirah]], [[Al Wusta Governorate (Oman)|Al Wusta]], and [[Dhofar Governorate|Dhofar]] Governorates , [[Oman]]\n| South     = {{flagicon|Yemen}}[[Hadhramaut Governorate]], [[Yemen]]\n| Southwest = [[Najran Region]]\n| West      = [[Riyadh Region]]\n| Northwest = {{flagicon|Iraq}}[[Al Muthanna Governorate]], [[Iraq]]<br>[[Northern Borders Region]]\n}}\n\n{{Regions of Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Saudi Arabia topics}}\n{{Saudi cities}}\n\n[[Category:Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia| ]]\n[[Category:Geography of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Saudi Arabia]]\n", "name_user": "AccordingClass", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_Province,_Saudi_Arabia"}
